{"id":"astro-ph/0111516","submitter":"Avery Broderick","authors":"A.E. Broderick (1), M. Prakash (2), J.M. Lattimer (2) ((1) Caltech,\n  Pasadena, California, (2) State University of New York at Stony Brook, Stony\n  Brook, New York)","title":"Effects of Strong Magnetic Fields in Strange Baryonic Matter","comments":"12 pages, 3 figures. To be submitted to Phys. Lett. B","journal-ref":"Phys.Lett. B531 (2002) 167-174","doi":"10.1016/S0370-2693(01)01514-3","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We investigate the effects of very strong magnetic fields upon the equation\nof state of dense bayonic matter in which hyperons are present. In the presence\nof a magnetic field, the equation of state above nuclear density is\nsignificantly affected both by Landau quantization and magnetic moment\ninteractions, but only for field strengths $B>5\\times10^{18}$ G. The former\ntends to soften the EOS and increase proton and lepton abundances, while the\nlatter produces an overall stiffening of the EOS. Each results in a supression\nof hyperons relative to the field-free case. The structure of a neutron star\nis, however, primarily determined by the magnetic field stress. We utilize\nexisting general relativistic magneto-hydrostatic calculations to demonstrate\nthat maximum average fields within a stable neutron are limited to values $B\\le\n1-3 \\times10^{18}$ G. This is not large enough to significantly influence\nparticle compositions or the matter pressure, unless fluctuations dominate the\naverage field strengths in the interior or configurations with significantly\nlarger field gradients are considered.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 Nov 2001 22:11:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
{"id":"astro-ph/0111517","submitter":"Henry E. Kandrup","authors":"Henry E. Kandrup and Ioannis V. Sideris","title":"Chaos in cuspy triaxial galaxies with a supermassive black hole: a\n  simple toy model","comments":"22 pages, including 12 FIGURES, to appear in Celestial Mechanics and\n  Dynamical Astronomy","journal-ref":"Celestial Mech. 82 (2002) 61-81","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  This paper summarises an investigation of chaos in a toy potential which\nmimics much of the behaviour observed for the more realistic triaxial\ngeneralisations of the Dehnen potentials, which have been used to model cuspy\ntriaxial galaxies both with and without a supermassive black hole. The\npotential is the sum of an anisotropic harmonic oscillator potential,\n  V_o=(1/2)*(a^{2}x^{2}+b^{2}y^{2}+c^{2}z^{2}), and a spherical Plummer\npotential,\n  V_o=-M_{BH}/(r^{2}+e^{2})^{1/2} with r^{2}=x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}. Attention\nfocuses on three issues related to the properties of ensembles of chaotic\norbits which impact on chaotic mixing and the possibility of constructing\nself-consistent equilibria: (1) What fraction of the orbits are chaotic? (2)\nHow sensitive are the chaotic orbits, i.e., how large are their largest (short\ntime) Lyapunov exponents? (3) To what extent is the motion of chaotic orbits\nimpeded by Arnold webs, i.e.,, how `sticky' are the chaotic orbits? These\nquestions are explored as functions of the axis ratio a:b:c, black hole mass\nM_BH, softening length e, and energy E with the aims of understanding how the\nmanifestations of chaos depend on the shape of the system and why the black\nhole generates chaos. The simplicity of the model makes it amenable to a\nperturbative analysis. That it mimics the behaviour of more complicated\npotentials suggests that much of this behaviour should be generic.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 Nov 2001 22:13:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
